RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) is an AI technique that combines information retrieval with large language models (LLMs) to produce more accurate, up-to-date, and context-aware responses.

R => Retrieval [ Fetch the most relevant information from database ]
A => Augmented [ Put the context with prompt ]
G => Generations [ LLM generates the answer ]




query ==> APP [ uses DB ] => send/receive req/res to/from LLM .

uses DB like Vector for similar data
How RAG works

Instead of relying only on what the language model learned during training, RAG follows these steps:


The LLM uses both:
Its general knowledge
The retrieved information
It produces a response grounded in the retrieved documents.


          User Question
                │
                ▼
        Embedding Model
                │
                ▼
        Vector Database
      (find similar documents)
                │
                ▼
      Relevant Documents
                │
                ▼
    Prompt + Retrieved Context
                │
                ▼
         Large Language Model
                │
                ▼
             Final Answer


Why use RAG?
Limited Memory / Context Limit /   hallucinations

More accurate: Answers are based on actual documents.
Up-to-date: No need to retrain the model when documents change.
Reduced hallucinations: The model is less likely to invent facts.
Private knowledge: Works with proprietary or internal data.


RAG solves this one by

fetching only most relevant pieces of data from Databases
Feeding them into the prompt , so the LLM has the right context
Reducing hallucinations and improving the accuracy + trustworthyness